# Proposal Defense (Condensed)

**Purpose:** Prepare for PhD/Master's proposal defense.

**Links to:** phd-proposal, research-question, research-design, defense-prep, milestone-tracker

---

## Proposal vs Thesis Defense

| Aspect | Proposal | Thesis |
|--------|----------|--------|
| Stage | Beginning | End |
| Content | Plan + preliminary | Completed work |
| Focus | Feasibility, novelty | Contributions, rigor |
| Duration | 1-2 hours | 2-3 hours |

## Slide Structure (20-30 slides, 45-60 min)

1-2: Title & Outline (1 min)
3-5: Background & Motivation (5 min)
6-8: Problem Statement (5 min)
9-11: Research Questions (5 min)
12-14: Literature Review (8 min)
15-19: Proposed Methodology (12 min)
20-22: Preliminary Results (5 min)
23-24: Evaluation Plan (3 min)
25-26: Timeline (2 min)
27-28: Contributions & Impact (2 min)
29: Questions (30 sec)
30: Backup Slides

## Common Questions

Problem: "Why important?", "Who benefits?", "What if we don't solve?"
Literature: "Considered [alternative]?", "Differs from [paper]?"
Method: "Why this approach?", "What if hypothesis wrong?"
Evaluation: "Why these datasets/metrics?", "How many seeds?"
Timeline: "Is this realistic?", "Backup plan?"

## Q&A Strategy

1. Listen fully, don't interrupt
2. Clarify if needed
3. Answer directly (yes/no first)
4. Be honest about weaknesses
5. Take notes on suggestions

## Response Templates

"Why this approach?": reasons + comparison to alternative + acknowledge limitation
"What if fails?": backup plan + learning value
"I don't know": initial thought + plan to investigate

## Post-Defense

Within 1 week: thank committee, document feedback, create action plan
Within 1 month: address comments, revise proposal, update timeline
